          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Given the very rece=
nt atmospherics of the presidential race=E2=80=94the feel-good rise of <b>K=
amala Harris</b> and the embittered bunkering down of<b> Donald Trump</b>=
=E2=80=94one could assume it=E2=80=99s a whole new ballgame up and down the=
 ballot, with Democrats anticipating a very good November. But according to=
 a round of calls I made to operatives in both parties, the fight for contr=
ol of Congress seems to be returning to the equilibrium that predated Trump=
=E2=80=99s assassination attempt and <b>Biden</b>=E2=80=99s exit: a tough, =
district-by-district slog to the gavel.<br/><br/><ul style=3D"margin:0;colo=
r:#000000;font-size:16px;line-height:30px;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;list=
-style-type:square;mso-special-format:bullet"><li><i>Small gains</i>: Polls=
ters have been busy in the field over the past two weeks trying to make sen=
se of the new environment, or whether there even
<i>is</i> a new environment. Strategists tell me that they=E2=80=99re seein=
g the Harris surge=E2=80=94or, in Republican parlance, =E2=80=9Csugar high=
=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94showing up in polling. But the down-ballot races seem lar=
gely unaffected, increasing the odds of split tickets in the fall. Yes, Dem=
ocrats are enjoying some Kamalamentum following the July polling dip that j=
olted <b>Nancy Pelosi</b> into action, but =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s a nudge, n=
ot a punch,=E2=80=9D as one Republican pollster told me. <br/><br/></li><li=
><i>Survey says=E2=80=A6</i>: Don=E2=80=99t expect to see a lot of new cong=
ressional polling right away, however. As several operatives noted, there=
=E2=80=99s limited R.O.I. to these pricey surveys in such a volatile nation=
al political environment. While some campaigns will be in the field over th=
e next week or so, they=E2=80=99re generally less interested in polling hea=
d-to-head matchups than in learning how to structure their messaging by ask=
ing respondents about issues. Indeed, operatives in both parties tell me th=
ey won=E2=80=99t
feel confident about the trajectory of the race until pollsters gather more=
 data in early- to mid-September. <br/><br/></li><li><i>Don=E2=80=99t count=
 out the G.O.P.</i>: Despite the <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/=
eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dSU1dvUXBFci16cGtIV191RFBSaz0iLCJ=
ocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvaW5zaWRlLXRoZS1sYXRlc3QtdHJ1bXB3b3JsZC10dX=
Jtb2lsLz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249VGhlK0Jlc3QrJTI2K1RoZStCcmlnaHRlc3QrLStTVUJTQ1JJQ=
kVSUyslMjg4JTJGMTIlMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jb250ZW50PVRoZStCZXN0KyUyNitUaGUr=
QnJpZ2h0ZXN0Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4NyUyRjI0JTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXV=
tPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT=
1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpb=
mtfaWQiOjk4MzAxM30/caa4802c4bbdb75ab2a507a3f42a27978e1ef8f872f1fbd9305dbfa3=
b26d0782" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" cla=
ss=3D"sdf">turmoil inside the Trump campaign</a></u>, Republicans are not r=
eady to concede anything at the presidential level, and they anticipate tha=
t Democratic polling will cool after the D.N.C. in Chicago. But if Trump <i=
>does</i> falter, it=E2=80=99s worth noting that G.O.P. House and Senate ca=
ndidates outperformed expectations in 2016 and 2020. In both cycles, the od=
ds were that Trump would lose, and voters seemed inclined to vote for Repub=
lican candidates as a check on a Democratic administration. Split-ticket vo=
ting will be a hot topic this fall, focusing on =E2=80=9CHarris
Republicans=E2=80=9D who will grudgingly vote for Harris but then check the=
 box for conservatives down the ballot.<br/> </li><br/><li><i>The counterar=
gument</i>: Other operatives note that Harris=E2=80=99s momentum could snow=
ball into a veritable <b>Obama</b>-esque wave that results in Democrats win=
ning the House <i>and </i>the Senate in November, as in 2008. Rally crowds =
don=E2=80=99t win elections, but they do whip up the base=E2=80=99s enthusi=
asm, which translates into eager door knockers, stronger local parties, and=
 repeat small-dollar donations. Vibes can=E2=80=99t vote, but Democrats fee=
l good about this cycle for the first time in a long time. It=E2=80=99s not=
 so much swagger as a return to the =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99d rather be us than=
 them=E2=80=9D mentality=E2=80=94even if the election truly is a coin toss.=
</li></ul></td>
